+summaryLines.push(`The identifier column patient_id was ignored. Mean pfs_months was ${round(ySummary.mean, 5)} months (SD ${round(ySummary.sd, 5)}, range ${round(ySummary.min, 5)} to ${round(ySummary.max, 5)}).`);
+summaryLines.push("");
+summaryLines.push("Main effects:");
+summaryLines.push(`The dominant univariable and adjusted main effect was feature_044. In the all-main-effects model, each 1-SD increase in feature_044 corresponded to +${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_044"), 5)} months of pfs_months (p=${formatP(adjustedP("feature_044"))}).`);
+summaryLines.push(`Other strong adjusted main effects were feature_027 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_027"), 5)} months/SD), feature_039 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_039"), 5)} months/SD), feature_046 (+${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_046"), 5)} months/SD), feature_015 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_015"), 5)} months/SD), feature_037 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_037"), 5)} months/SD), feature_031 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_031"), 5)} months/SD), feature_004 (+${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_004"), 5)} months/SD), feature_062 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_062"), 5)} months/SD), feature_069 (+${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_069"), 5)} months/SD), and feature_063 (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_063"), 5)} months/SD), all with very small p-values.`);
+summaryLines.push(`A smaller independent negative effect for feature_033 was also present (${round(adjustedPerSd("feature_033"), 5)} months/SD, p=${formatP(adjustedP("feature_033"))}). Nominal small effects for feature_005, feature_032, feature_017, and feature_059 were much weaker and should be treated as secondary.`);
+summaryLines.push("");
+summaryLines.push("Interaction and subgroup heterogeneity:");
+summaryLines.push(`An exhaustive pairwise screen of standardized two-feature products found a concentrated interaction pattern. After adjustment for all 77 main effects, the largest valid interactions involved feature_046 with feature_031 (${round(adjustedInteractionResult("feature_031", "feature_046").beta, 5)} months per SD-product), feature_069 (+${round(adjustedInteractionResult("feature_069", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), feature_062 (${round(adjustedInteractionResult("feature_062", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), feature_063 (${round(adjustedInteractionResult("feature_063", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), and feature_010 (+${round(adjustedInteractionResult("feature_010", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), all p<1e-300.`);
+summaryLines.push(`A joint model containing all main effects plus the top 20 interaction candidates preserved the same feature_046-centered heterogeneity for feature_031 by feature_046 (${round(jointInteractionResult("feature_031", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), feature_069 by feature_046 (+${round(jointInteractionResult("feature_069", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), feature_062 by feature_046 (${round(jointInteractionResult("feature_062", "feature_046").beta, 5)}), and feature_063 by feature_046 (${round(jointInteractionResult("feature_063", "feature_046").beta, 5)}). The feature_010 by feature_046 term was positive in the single-interaction model but attenuated in the joint model (+${round(jointInteractionResult("feature_010", "feature_046").beta, 5)}, p=${formatP(jointInteractionResult("feature_010", "feature_046").p)}), so it was not independently supported after accounting for the other interaction candidates.`);
+summaryLines.push(`Raw subgroup checks agreed directionally. For feature_031 and feature_046, the 2x2 difference-in-differences was ${round(binary031046.did, 5)} months, indicating the positive feature_046 contrast was attenuated when feature_031=1. For feature_069 and feature_046, the raw difference-in-differences was +${round(binary069046.did, 5)} months, indicating the feature_046 contrast was amplified when feature_069=1.`);
+summaryLines.push(`For continuous feature_062, the unadjusted slope was ${round(slope062By046[0].slopePerSd, 5)} months/SD when feature_046=0 and ${round(slope062By046[1].slopePerSd, 5)} months/SD when feature_046=1, matching the negative feature_062 by feature_046 interaction. For feature_044, the positive slope was weaker when feature_039=1 (${round(slope044By039[1].slopePerSd, 5)} months/SD) than when feature_039=0 (+${round(slope044By039[0].slopePerSd, 5)} months/SD).`);
+summaryLines.push("");
+summaryLines.push("Nonlinearity:");
+summaryLines.push(`Quadratic probes suggested that the linear feature_044 effect had a statistically detectable but small curved component (${round(quadraticResults.find((item) => item.name === "feature_044").betaQuadratic, 5)} months for standardized z^2, p=${formatP(quadraticResults.find((item) => item.name === "feature_044").pQuadratic)}). The feature_062 quadratic term was ${round(quadraticResults.find((item) => item.name === "feature_062").betaQuadratic, 5)} months (p=${formatP(quadraticResults.find((item) => item.name === "feature_062").pQuadratic)}), much smaller than its linear and interaction terms.`);
+summaryLines.push("");
+summaryLines.push("Overall conclusion:");
+summaryLines.push(`The cohort shows a strong multivariable signal for pfs_months. Main effects explain substantial variation (R^2=${round(1 - allMainModel.rss / yCenteredSS, 6)}), and adding the leading interaction candidates increases R^2 to ${round(jointInteractions.r2, 6)}. The most clinically interpretable pattern is not a single marker alone but heterogeneity around feature_046: its favorable association with pfs_months is reduced in feature_031=1 and feature_063=1 contexts, increased in feature_069=1 contexts, and coupled with a stronger adverse feature_062 slope. The apparent feature_010 enhancement was not robust in the joint interaction model.`);
+
+fs.writeFileSync(path.join(process.cwd(), "transcript.json"), `${JSON.stringify(transcript, null, 2)}\n`);
+fs.writeFileSync(path.join(process.cwd(), "analysis_summary.txt"), `${summaryLines.join("\n")}\n`);
+
+console.log(JSON.stringify({
+  rows: y.length,
+  main_r2: round(1 - allMainModel.rss / yCenteredSS, 8),
+  joint_r2: round(jointInteractions.r2, 8),
+  top_adjusted_main: adjustedMain.slice(0, 12).map((item) => ({ name: item.name, betaPerSd: round(item.betaPerSd, 6), p: pForJson(item.p) })),
+  top_joint_interactions: jointInteractions.rows.slice(0, 10).map((item) => ({ a: item.a, b: item.b, beta: round(item.beta, 6), p: pForJson(item.p) })),
+}, null, 2));

